# Ray Cluster Migration Plan
**Prepared:** 2026-06-26  
**Namespace:** ray  
**Window:** Next scheduled upgrade cycle (do not apply before team review)

---

## 1. Current State

### Deployments

| Resource     | Replicas | Image                  | CPU Request | CPU Limit | Mem Request | Mem Limit |
|--------------|----------|------------------------|-------------|-----------|-------------|-----------|
| ray-head     | 1        | rayproject/ray:2.9.0   | (none)      | (none)    | (none)      | (none)    |
| ray-worker   | 1        | rayproject/ray:2.9.0   | (none)      | (none)    | (none)      | (none)    |

**ray-head startup flags:** `--include-dashboard=false --num-cpus=0 --port=6379`  
**ray-worker startup flags:** `--address=ray-head:6379 --num-cpus=1`

### Services

| Service   | Type      | Cluster-IP     | Ports       | External |
|-----------|-----------|----------------|-------------|----------|
| ray-head  | ClusterIP | 10.96.159.61   | 6379/TCP    | none     |

The Ray Dashboard (port 8265) is **not** started and **not** exposed.  
No LoadBalancer or NodePort service exists.

### Notable observations
- Both deployments use identical image versions (2.9.0).
- No resource requests or limits are set on either container — the pods are running "best-effort" QoS class, meaning they may be the first evicted under node pressure.
- Only the GCS port (6379) is reachable within the cluster; the dashboard is disabled in the head startup command.
- Worker count is 1, providing no horizontal redundancy for task execution.

---

## 2. Proposed Changes

### 2.1 Image Upgrade: 2.9.0 → 2.10.0

Upgrade both `ray-head` and `ray-worker` to `rayproject/ray:2.10.0`.  
Ray 2.10 adds stability fixes for the GCS fault-tolerance path and improved
scheduling performance. Both components must be upgraded together to maintain
protocol compatibility.

**Risk:** Rolling restart of head will briefly disconnect workers; they will
reconnect automatically once the new head pod is Ready. Schedule during a
low-traffic window.

### 2.2 Scale Workers: 1 → 3 replicas

Increase `ray-worker` replicas from 1 to 3 to allow parallel task execution
and tolerate single-worker failures without stalling running jobs.

### 2.3 Add Resource Requests and Limits

Set explicit CPU and memory bounds on both containers so the pods receive
Burstable (or Guaranteed) QoS and the Kubernetes scheduler can make informed
placement decisions.

Proposed values (tune to actual cluster node capacity):

| Container  | CPU Request | CPU Limit | Memory Request | Memory Limit |
|------------|-------------|-----------|----------------|--------------|
| ray-head   | 500m        | 1000m     | 512Mi          | 1Gi          |
| ray-worker | 500m        | 2000m     | 1Gi            | 2Gi          |

### 2.4 Expose the Ray Dashboard

Enable the dashboard in the head startup command and add port 8265 to the
`ray-head` Service so operators can inspect cluster state and job progress
through the Ray UI.

---

## 3. Exact kubectl Commands (DO NOT RUN — for review only)

### Step 1: Upgrade ray-head image and enable dashboard, add resource limits

```bash
kubectl -n ray patch deployment ray-head --type=strategic --patch '{
  "spec": {
    "template": {
      "spec": {
        "containers": [{
          "name": "ray-head",
          "image": "rayproject/ray:2.10.0",
          "command": ["sh", "-c", "ray start --head --node-ip-address=\"${MY_POD_IP}\" --port=6379 --include-dashboard=true --dashboard-port=8265 --num-cpus=0 --block\n"],
          "resources": {
            "requests": {"cpu": "500m", "memory": "512Mi"},
            "limits":   {"cpu": "1000m", "memory": "1Gi"}
          }
        }]
      }
    }
  }
}'
```

### Step 2: Upgrade ray-worker image and add resource limits

```bash
kubectl -n ray patch deployment ray-worker --type=strategic --patch '{
  "spec": {
    "template": {
      "spec": {
        "containers": [{
          "name": "ray-worker",
          "image": "rayproject/ray:2.10.0",
          "resources": {
            "requests": {"cpu": "500m", "memory": "1Gi"},
            "limits":   {"cpu": "2000m", "memory": "2Gi"}
          }
        }]
      }
    }
  }
}'
```

### Step 3: Scale workers to 3 replicas

```bash
kubectl -n ray scale deployment ray-worker --replicas=3
```

### Step 4: Add dashboard port to ray-head Service

```bash
kubectl -n ray patch service ray-head --type=strategic --patch '{
  "spec": {
    "ports": [
      {"name": "gcs",       "port": 6379,  "targetPort": 6379},
      {"name": "dashboard", "port": 8265,  "targetPort": 8265}
    ]
  }
}'
```

### Step 5: Verify rollout

```bash
kubectl -n ray rollout status deployment/ray-head
kubectl -n ray rollout status deployment/ray-worker
kubectl -n ray get pods -o wide
kubectl -n ray get svc ray-head
```

---

## 4. Rollback Plan

If any step causes instability, revert with:

```bash
# Revert ray-head
kubectl -n ray patch deployment ray-head --type=strategic --patch '{
  "spec": {
    "template": {
      "spec": {
        "containers": [{
          "name": "ray-head",
          "image": "rayproject/ray:2.9.0",
          "command": ["sh", "-c", "ray start --head --node-ip-address=\"${MY_POD_IP}\" --port=6379 --include-dashboard=false --num-cpus=0 --block\n"],
          "resources": {}
        }]
      }
    }
  }
}'

# Revert ray-worker image and scale
kubectl -n ray patch deployment ray-worker --type=strategic --patch '{
  "spec": {
    "replicas": 1,
    "template": {
      "spec": {
        "containers": [{
          "name": "ray-worker",
          "image": "rayproject/ray:2.9.0",
          "resources": {}
        }]
      }
    }
  }
}'

# Revert Service to GCS port only
kubectl -n ray patch service ray-head --type=strategic --patch '{
  "spec": {
    "ports": [
      {"name": "gcs", "port": 6379, "targetPort": 6379}
    ]
  }
}'
```

---

## 5. Pre-Change Checklist

- [ ] Confirm `rayproject/ray:2.10.0` image is available and pull-tested on cluster nodes
- [ ] Verify node capacity can accommodate 2 additional worker pods (1Gi RAM + 0.5 CPU each)
- [ ] Notify team of maintenance window (head restart will briefly disconnect all workers)
- [ ] Ensure no long-running Ray jobs are active when rolling the head deployment
- [ ] Back up any persistent state if custom actor checkpointing is in use

---

*This document is a review artifact only. No changes have been applied to the live cluster.*
